{{ŚćĀŚĻ≤ŚćĀšļĆśĒĮ}}
'''Otsu''' (šĻô, "kinoto") is the second of the {{ill|Heavenly Stems|lt=Ten Heavenly Stems|8=en|ja|ŚćĀŚĻ≤}}.

According to the {{ill|Yin-Yang Five Elements theory|ja|ťôįťôĹšļĒŤ°ĆŤ™¨}}, it is assigned to the {{ill|yin|ja|ťôį}} aspect of the {{ill|wood element|ja|śú®}}. Hence, in Japan, it is also referred to as "kinoto" (meaning "younger brother of wood").

== Overview ==
* The origin of the kanji "šĻô" has been subject to various proposals, but no definitive theory has been established.<ref>{{Citation| author=Yu Shengwu| year=1996| title=Jiaguwen Zhilin (ÁĒ≤ť™®śĖáŚ≠óŤ©Āśěó)| location=Beijing| publisher=Zhonghua Book Company| isbn=7-101-01430-5| pages=1178‚Äď80}}</ref> The character is used as a borrowed form to denote the second in the sequence of the Ten Heavenly Stems.
* When the Ten Heavenly Stems are used for ranking, "Otsu" signifies the second position. It is also used in classification systems, such as "Otsu-type" (šĻôÁ®ģ) or "Otsu-class" (šĻôť°ě). While these terms are simply labels for categories, many mistakenly believe that "Otsu" implies inferiority compared to "Kou" (ÁĒ≤, the first stem). For example, in the classification of {{ill|shochu|ja|ÁĄľťÖé}}, there are "Kou-class" and "Otsu-class" varieties. To avoid the misconception that "Otsu-class" is inferior, it is often referred to as "honkaku shochu" (śú¨ś†ľÁĄľťÖé), meaning "authentic shochu."
* Additionally, expressions like "difficult to determine between Kou and Otsu" (ÁĒ≤šĻôšĽė„ĀĎ„ĀĆ„Āü„ĀĄ) suggest a comparison where "Kou" is perceived as superior and "Otsu" as lesser. In {{ill|calligraphy|ja|śõłťĀď}} and other disciplines, these terms are used to indicate progress or ranking in proficiency tests.
* Years ending with the digit 5 in the {{ill|Gregorian calendar|ja|Ť•Ņśö¶}} correspond to the year of "Otsu." The alternate name for such years is "{{ill|Zhanmeng|ja|śóÉŤíô}}."<ref>{{Cite web |title=Ancient Alternative Names and Explanations for the Heavenly Stems and Earthly Branches |url=https://www.cidianwang.com/shufazuopin/jiaocheng/932596.htm |website=www.cidianwang.com |access-date=2024-03-08}}</ref>
* The opposite counterpart of "Otsu" is {{ill|Kou|ja|Śļö}}.
* The {{ill|lucky direction|ja|śĀĶśĖĻ}} (eho) associated with Otsu is slightly west of southwest (255 degrees).

